message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms are consistent with Hirschsprung disease, which is caused by the failure of specialized cells to migrate into the intestine during embryonic development. The distended abdomen and crying with palpation are indicative of bowel obstruction, which is commonly seen in Hirschsprung disease. Meckel diverticulum presents with painless rectal bleeding, DiGeorge syndrome with immunodeficiency and cardiac defects, and duodenal atresia with bilious vomiting.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms of a fussy baby who is not feeding well, gaining weight, and having a distended abdomen suggest Hirschsprung disease. This disease is caused by the failure of specialized cells to migrate, leading to a lack of ganglion cells in the rectum and colon, resulting in constipation and abdominal distension. Meckel diverticulum is a congenital abnormality where a portion of the intestine protrudes into the umbilicus. DiGeorge syndrome is a genetic disorder that affects the development of the thymus and parathyroid glands. Duodenal atresia is a blockage in the first part of the small intestine, leading to vomiting and abdominal distension.
